115. in Cresphonte. Cresphontes, king of Messenia, was put to death, together with his sons, by the Optimates, who disliked his popularity. His fate furnished Euripides with materials for a tragedy, of which the passage translated by Cicero, and a few other fr,agments are all that remain. The passage to which we allude is as follows: ·
